In [8]:
# Whenever you have many outliers: Keep them for clustering as Clustering may create seperate cluetsres for all these outliers.
# Less Outlier: Devieate the cluster center For treating them you can cap them or drop them
# Capping: less outliers
# Remove: Good number of data points

q1 = dataset["gdpp"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["gdpp"].quantile(0.80)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["gdpp"]>=q1) & (dataset["gdpp"]<=q2)]


q1 = dataset["life_expec"].quantile(0.01)
q2 = dataset["life_expec"].quantile(1)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["life_expec"]>=q1) & (dataset["life_expec"]<=q2)]


q1 = dataset["inflation"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["inflation"].quantile(0.975)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["inflation"]>=q1) & (dataset["inflation"]<=q2)]


q1 = dataset["health"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["health"].quantile(0.995)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["health"]>=q1) & (dataset["health"]<=q2)]

q1 = dataset["imports"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["imports"].quantile(0.995)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["imports"]>=q1) & (dataset["imports"]<=q2)]


q1 = dataset["child_mort"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["child_mort"].quantile(0.995)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["child_mort"]>=q1) & (dataset["child_mort"]<=q2)]

q1 = dataset["income"].quantile(0.00)
q2 = dataset["income"].quantile(0.995)
dataset = dataset[(dataset["income"]>=q1) & (dataset["income"]<=q2)]

Calculating Hopkins¶

In [19]:
from sklearn.neighbors import NearestNeighbors
from random import sample
from numpy.random import uniform
import numpy as np
from math import isnan
 
def hopkins(X):
    d = X.shape[1]
    #d = len(vars) # columns
    n = len(X) # rows
    m = int(0.1 * n) 
    nbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=1).fit(X.values)
 
    rand_X = sample(range(0, n, 1), m)
 
    ujd = []
    wjd = []
    for j in range(0, m):
        u_dist, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(uniform(np.amin(X,axis=0),np.amax(X,axis=0),d).reshape(1, -1), 2, return_distance=True)
        ujd.append(u_dist[0][1])
        w_dist, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(X.iloc[rand_X[j]].values.reshape(1, -1), 2, return_distance=True)
        wjd.append(w_dist[0][1])
 
    H = sum(ujd) / (sum(ujd) + sum(wjd))
    if isnan(H):
        print(ujd, wjd)
        H = 0
 
    return H

K-Means Clustering¶

Question: Look at the silhouette score plot and choose the optimal number of cluster¶

In [22]:
# Silhoiette score analysis
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
ss = []
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(dataset3_1)
    ss.append([k, silhouette_score(dataset3_1, kmeans.labels_)])
plt.plot(pd.DataFrame(ss)[0], pd.DataFrame(ss)[1])
plt.savefig("silhouette.png")

Analysis:¶

We observe that based on the graph obtained the optimal number of clusters are 3

Question: Look at the Elbow Curve plot and choose the optimal number of cluster¶

In [23]:
# Elbow curve analysis for choosing the number of clusters
ss = []
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(dataset3_1)
    ss.append([k, kmeans.inertia_])
plt.plot(pd.DataFrame(ss)[0], pd.DataFrame(ss)[1])
plt.savefig("elbow.png")

Analysis¶

We observe that based on the graph obtained the optimal number of clusters are 3
